  "case_id": "D2N092",
  "method": "cap_event",
  "template": "sectioned",
  "summary_text": "Chief Complaint\nPain in the distal radius of the right arm following a tennis injury.\n\nHistory of Present Illness\nThe patient reports pain in the distal radius of the right arm following a tennis injury. He describes hitting a backhand shot, where the ball contacted the net pole, resulting in a direct impact to his arm. He experienced immediate swelling, which was moderate in extent. He reports mild pain with wrist movement and tenderness to palpation. He denies numbness or significant weakness in his hand. He has a past history of a fall while raking leaves, resulting in a stab wound to the forearm, which he describes as being treated with stitches. He also has a history of allergies and takes flonase for them. He has no prior surgeries.\n\nFindings\nPhysical examination reveals tenderness to palpation over the distal radius of the right arm. Range of motion is limited due to pain. No signs of fracture are observed on visual inspection. The patient reports mild pain with wrist flexion and extension.\n\nAssessment\nStrain and contusion of the right distal radius muscle.\n\nPlan\nPrescribe ice packs for 20 minutes every 2-3 hours. Recommend motrin 800 mg three times daily with food for pain and inflammation. Follow up in one week if symptoms do not improve. Order x-rays to rule out fracture.",
  "reference_summary": "CC:\n\nRight arm pain.\n\nHPI:\n\nMs. Martinez is a 43-year-old female who presents today for an evaluation of right arm pain after she hitting her arm on a pole while playing tennis. She had mild swelling at the time. There is pain with motion. She denies any numbness or tingling in her hand. She has a past medical history of allergies and takes Flonase.\n\nEXAM\n\nExamination of the left wrist shows tenderness over the distal radius and pain with flexion of the wrist and thumb.\n\nRESULTS\n\nX-rays of the left wrist show no obvious signs of acute fracture or other abnormality.\n\nIMPRESSION\n\nRight wrist sprain.\n\nPLAN\n\nAt this point, I discussed the diagnosis and treatment options with the patient. I have recommended ice and anti-inflammatory medications. I am prescribing Motrin, 800 mg to take 3 times a day with food. She will follow up with me in 1 week or as needed.",
